# Code Style and Structure

## Directory Structure

Follow this structure for organizing your codebase:

```sh
app/
├── api.ts                  # Root API configuration
├── components/             # Shared components
│   ├── ui/                # UI components
│   └── features/          # Feature components
├── lib/                   # Shared utilities
│   ├── client/           # Client-only code
│   ├── server/           # Server-only code
│   └── shared/           # Shared code
└── routes/                # File-based routes
    ├── __root.tsx        # Root layout
    ├── api/              # API routes
    │   ├── auth/         # Auth-related endpoints
    │   │   └── $.ts     # Auth handler (catch-all)
    │   └── send.ts      # Email sending endpoint
    ├── _public/          # Public routes
    ├── _auth/           # Auth routes
    └── _app/            # Protected routes
```

## File Naming Conventions

1. Route Files:

   - `__root.tsx` - Root layout
   - `route.tsx` - Layout files
   - `index.tsx` - Page components
   - `[param].tsx` - Dynamic routes

2. API Routes:

   - `$.ts` - Catch-all handlers
   - `[feature].ts` - Feature-specific endpoints

3. Component Files:

   - Use PascalCase
   - Suffix with type: `.component.tsx`
   - Example: `UserProfile.component.tsx`

4. Server Functions:

   - Prefix with `$`
   - Use camelCase after prefix
   - Group in feature-specific files
   - Example: `$getUser`, `$updateProfile`

5. Type Files:
   - Suffix with `.types.ts`
   - Example: `user.types.ts`

## Code Style

### Imports

1. Order imports:

   ```typescript
   // External dependencies
   import { useState } from 'react';
   import { createServerFn } from '@tanstack/start';

   // Internal dependencies
   import { UserProfile } from '~/components/features/user';
   import { Button } from '~/components/ui/button';

   // Types
   import type { User } from '~/lib/shared/types';
   ```

### Variables and Functions

1. Use descriptive names:

   ```typescript
   // ✅ Good
   const isUserAuthenticated = true;
   const handleProfileUpdate = () => {};

   // ❌ Bad
   const auth = true;
   const update = () => {};
   ```

2. Use proper type annotations:

   ```typescript
   // ✅ Good
   const user: User = { id: 1, name: 'John' };
   function getUser(id: string): Promise<User> {}

   // ❌ Bad
   const user = { id: 1, name: 'John' };
   function getUser(id) {}
   ```

### Server Functions

1. Organization:

   ```typescript
   // ✅ Good - Grouped by feature
   // routes/api/users/index.ts
   export const $getUser = createServerFn({ method: 'GET' })
     .handler(async ({ params }) => {
       // Implementation
     });

   // ❌ Bad - Mixed with components
   function UserProfile() {
     const $getUser = createServerFn({ method: 'GET' });
     return <div>...</div>;
   }
   ```

2. Naming:

   ```typescript
   // ✅ Good
   export const $createUser = createServerFn({ method: 'POST' });
   export const $updateProfile = createServerFn({ method: 'PUT' });

   // ❌ Bad
   export const createUser = createServerFn({ method: 'POST' });
   export const $User_Update = createServerFn({ method: 'PUT' });
   ```

### API Routes

1. Organization:

   ```typescript
   // ✅ Good - Catch-all handler
   // routes/api/auth/$.ts
   export const APIRoute = createAPIFileRoute('/api/auth/$')({
     GET: ({ request }) => auth.handler(request),
     POST: ({ request }) => auth.handler(request),
   });

   // ✅ Good - Feature-specific endpoint
   // routes/api/send.ts
   export const APIRoute = createAPIFileRoute('/api/send')({
     POST: async ({ request }) => {
       // Implementation
     },
   });

   // ❌ Bad - Mixed concerns
   export const APIRoute = createAPIFileRoute('/api/mixed')({
     GET: ({ request }) => {
       // Auth, email, and other mixed logic
     },
   });
   ```

2. Handler Focus:

   ```typescript
   // ✅ Good - Single responsibility
   export const APIRoute = createAPIFileRoute('/api/users')({
     GET: async ({ request }) => {
       const users = await db.users.findMany();
       return json(users);
     },
   });

   // ❌ Bad - Multiple responsibilities
   export const APIRoute = createAPIFileRoute('/api/users')({
     GET: async ({ request }) => {
       const users = await db.users.findMany();
       const posts = await db.posts.findMany();
       const comments = await db.comments.findMany();
       return json({ users, posts, comments });
     },
   });
   ```

## Error Handling

1. Use proper error boundaries:

   ```typescript
   // ✅ Good
   export function ErrorBoundary({ error }: { error: Error }) {
     return (
       <div role="alert">
         <p>Something went wrong:</p>
         <pre>{error.message}</pre>
       </div>
     );
   }
   ```

2. Handle async errors:

   ```typescript
   // ✅ Good
   try {
     const data = await $fetchData();
     return json(data);
   } catch (error) {
     if (error instanceof ValidationError) {
       return json({ error: error.message }, { status: 400 });
     }
     throw error;
   }
   ```

## Type Safety

1. Use `type` over `interface` for all type definitions:

   ```typescript
   // ✅ Good
   type UserData = {
     id: string;
     name: string;
   };

   type Props = {
     user: UserData;
     onUpdate: (user: UserData) => void;
   };

   // ❌ Bad - Don't use interface except in declare module
   interface UserData {
     id: string;
     name: string;
   }
   ```

2. Exception: Use `interface` only within `declare module` statements:

   ```typescript
   // ✅ Good - Interface in declare module is allowed
   declare module '@tanstack/react-router' {
     interface Register {
       router: ReturnType<typeof createRouter>;
     }
   }

   // ❌ Bad - Don't use interface outside declare module
   interface ComponentProps {
     children: React.ReactNode;
   }
   ```

3. Use proper type inference:

   ```typescript
   // ✅ Good
   const $getUser = createServerFn({ method: 'GET' })
     .input((data) => userSchema.parse(data))
     .handler(async ({ data }) => {
       return db.user.findUnique({ where: { id: data.id } });
     });

   // ❌ Bad
   const $getUser = createServerFn({ method: 'GET' }).handler(
     async ({ data }) => {
       return db.user.findUnique({ where: { id: data.id } });
     },
   );
   ```

## Performance

1. Use proper code splitting:

   ```typescript
   // ✅ Good
   const UserProfile = lazy(() => import('./UserProfile'));

   function App() {
     return (
       <Suspense fallback={<Loading />}>
         <UserProfile />
       </Suspense>
     );
   }
   ```

2. Implement proper caching:

   ```typescript
   // ✅ Good
   export const $getUsers = createServerFn({ method: 'GET' }).handler(
     async () => {
       return cache(() => db.users.findMany(), ['users'], { revalidate: 60 });
     },
   );
   ```

## Testing

1. Write proper tests:

   ```typescript
   // ✅ Good
   describe('UserProfile', () => {
     it('renders user information', async () => {
       render(<UserProfile userId="1" />);
       expect(await screen.findByText('John Doe')).toBeInTheDocument();
     });
   });
   ```

2. Use proper mocking:

   ```typescript
   // ✅ Good
   vi.mock('~/lib/server/db', () => ({
     db: {
       user: {
         findUnique: vi.fn().mockResolvedValue({
           id: '1',
           name: 'John Doe',
         }),
       },
     },
   }));
   ```
